segments.text: This is August 4th.
This is Bob Cornish, and we are in the office of Don Sweeney, the interim dean of the College of Architecture and Environmental Design.
Don, could you go over some of your early experience and how you came to be in planning?
My guess is probably sort of indirectly, but I think probably many of us do.
I was involved in
a master's degree program here in Texas A&M in health facilities architecture.
I started off with an interest in medicine early on in my undergraduate program, realized that I was interested in health and not medicine, and the two are not necessarily related, I discovered.
So I finished with a degree in English and along the way got to know a fellow on campus.
What year was that?
My class of 66.
got to know a fellow who was a student here in the College of Architecture, just entering a master's program that was going to concentrate on health facilities research.
So I entered that program as well because I was still interested in health and had always been interested in facilities.
And that program studied health care delivery generally.
We didn't just study facilities because
Facilities are simply the three-dimensional manifestation of programmatic endeavors.
So we were looking at the whole health care delivery system.
And in fact, our whole modus operandi was systems-oriented.
We took a very broad approach to problem solving under Gunther Schmidt's leadership, which you will recall, the Fuhrer.
The Quintero, yes.
Lord of the End.
It was just natural for me anyway.
I think I tend to be oriented that way anyway, naturally.

And so I studied health facilities planning and design, got the master's degree, and worked for a while in New York City with the Health and Hospital Planning Council of Southern New York in their architectural debate.
And I went to the Army to fulfill my obligation right in the middle of the Vietnam War.
Two years of that and I came back.
I was in Korea during that period.
And I came back to pursue a doctorate.
What year was that?
I came back in 1970.
I was interested in pursuing a doctorate in health facilities.
I actually did a study for the World Health Organization on national health planning in developing countries.
It started off to be a project on health facilities in developing countries, but it turned out that facilities are really not the issue.
They have architects and engineers as good as ours.
The problem was that the decision makers in those countries do not appreciate health as a valid point for investment of scarce resources.
They tend to want to focus on industrial projects.
instead of health and social services.
So the point we were trying to make is that a very important key to overall development of the country is the health and social service infrastructure.
And at that time, I was teaching in the Department of Architecture also.
Actually, as I finished the degree, I took over from Gunter in the building systems program that he was in charge of.
after he left for SUNY.
Yes, and the health planning courses were in the process of being formed at that time by Joe Sprague.
How did he spell his name?
Sprague was here in the research center also, part of that research team.
had a background in architecture and was responsible for developing four courses in college, two in architecture and two in planning.
I had two courses in health facilities design and two in health planning.
I inherited all those courses when he left.
So I moved from systems to an orientation towards health facilities.
And then to planning, I inherited those courses.
And then I became dean assistant, dean for research.
And when I went back to faculty full time, it was in the department of planning, looking after the health systems.
What year was that?
That was after Wolfgang became department head.
I think he arrived in 75.
I had to look at my resume.
I really don't remember.
But I went back full time on the faculty, working in the health systems program.
All along, all through that time, I was consulting with health institutions and health and social service agencies.
And also, I was very actively involved in the fiduciary capacity with regional boards and the regional planning commission.
the state and federal agencies on various committees and task forces and boards.
I was on the board of the American Health Planning Association.
I was on a big national task force in health planning and health service construction for the National Institute of Health and AGW, I guess, some time ago.
And also heads of NSF and a couple of firms in Washington and California.
I was also involved in, have been involved with regional health planning in Texas in all of its eras.
The first one was under Public Law 89-749, which was the Comprehensive Health Planning Act of 66, which Texas got into in the late 60s, early 70s.
Who was governor of?
Riscoe, I think.
Actually, it was Smith in Nebraska.
We had some health planning projects with the state health planning agency in the old research center, and I got involved with it during that era.
Then the subsequent, so I served as a member of the regional health planning advisory council in finding a charity for seven years, and then I got involved with regional alcoholism and drug abuse
services planning, and I chaired that for seven years.
And then I served on the statewide advisory council for the Texas Commission on Alcoholism and Drug Abuse for seven years.
I served on the state advisory council for the Emergency Medical Services Division of Texas Department of Health for another four years.
And I also chaired the regional emergency medical services planning group with the COG.
So I've chaired three different advisory councils for the Regional Planning Commission one time or another.
And I served as a board member on Humana Hospital in the rehab center and Blue Bonnet Psychiatric Center.
And I'm on the board of the, I'm chairman of the board of Green Bay right now.
I'm on the board with several different health and social service agencies.
Aside from your work with outside agencies, when you came into the planning department, you had been there for a year or two, as I remember.
And then we hired a part-time faculty member to help you.
And I can't remember your name.
Sharon Rothman.
How do you spell her last name?
R-O-T-H-M-E-L. She was quite good, as I recall.
She had a background in planning.
And she had a degree in planning.
And she had worked professionally as a health planner in Utah.
And she left because her husband left.
That's right.
Do you remember the day she joined us and left?
No, I don't.
That would be, it's a matter of record here at the university, somewhere, if we can find it.
We'll have to add it later.
During that period, the health planning program typically would run about six or seven students, and there were some very fine students.
Dan Yazak was one.
He's up in Montana still, I believe.
Yeah, he's an administrator, hospital administrator at Shodare Children's Hospital now, doing very well.
Mark McConathy, who did a master's and then a Ph.D. Another person who did that was Nora Smith-Cox.
Nora Smith-Cox, who is now in Wisconsin.
She has both a master's and a Ph.D.
and there were several others who were very fine and who had done well in the health plan field.
Wischmick, Frances Wischmick, she went through the health plan program and worked in that field and may still be working in that field in New Jersey, I think.
You know, those are notable.
Marina Weiss took a doctorate here under Jim Gardner, but her areas were social services planning, and she took all the health planning courses.
Very, very bright.
Now a senior aide with Senator Vinson.
Well, the program has sort of waxed and waned, depending upon sort of an irregular supply of students and projects.
The conclusion that I've come to is that one person does not a program make.
You really have to have more than just one person.
And that's really all we had.
For a long time I taught the health plan courses and the health facilities courses in the college and really maintained that health emphasis both in architecture and planning alone.
George Mann has been very active in health facilities in particular and has taken those courses in architecture.
I think it's a very important part of the planning program.

There certainly are opportunities, particularly in the health sector now, when health institutions are becoming more and more involved in the application of business technology and basic business practices to the delivery of health services.
Just a few years ago, it would have been obscene to see a full page ad in a newspaper from a hospital, but now it's fairly typical.
And you see ads and et cetera, cut rate specials, so to speak, for surgery, on and on.
So what we're seeing is that in an era of great and increasing competition, the health institutions are also very heavily regulated.
So they don't really have the area of price competition.
They have to find other ways to compete.
So it's very important that they plan effectively.
So strategic planning.
That's the current buzz word.
And the health sector is very important.
It's now that sometimes they're absolutely committed to it.
They were forced into it by the circumstances of the marketplace.
But also by regulation, there are various agencies that require that they have plans.
The health planning system of the federal government requires that.
Of course, that's dormant in Texas.
It's not operational at all.
Could you go into the history of that a bit?
I think that's particularly interesting in terms of the regional health planning sectors of Texas and their history and where we are now and where we have been.
Well, I think that Texas, in some ways,
has been a precursor of what has happened nationally in the area of health planning, regional health planning in particular.
The public law on 93-641, the National Health Planning and Resource Development, 74, mandated a nationwide health planning system.
It mandated heavy participation by citizens, consumers in particular.
gave the numerical edge on all the policy-making bodies to the consumers, as opposed to the providers of health services.
And it was very, I think, interestingly organized.

It was implemented, however, both in Texas and I think nationally, with too heavy a hand by some of the planning zealots and the consumer advocates, to the extent that they ultimately alienated the participants in the traditional
political arena of the health sector.
That arena has been dominated by what's called a very cozy triangle between health providers and health regulators and health bureaucracy and then politicians.
So that when the consumers were thrown in the middle of that,
They screwed up all the relationships.
They were irreverent.
They didn't make any deals with anybody.
They asked silly questions.
And it really screwed everything up.
So ultimately, it was just a...
Probably resented by the health providers.
They were heavily resented by everybody.
And they asked silly, naive questions about things that couldn't be answered very well.
For instance, in Texas, the state was divided up into 12...
health service areas, like super COG areas.
The one that we were in included the service areas for BEDC, CAPCO, and SITCOG, and HOTCOG.
Four COGs.
Four COG areas all together in one big super region.
Of course, these are
The cog areas are in the main, I think, fairly functional regions.
And they do, in fact, describe regional behavior.
I mean, Brazos Valley, believe it or not, College Station is the cultural hub.
And College Station Bryan and in HGAC, it works that way.
That, in fact, is fairly a good description of the region.
Central Texas Cog, the Harbor Texas Cog, Capital Area, ACOG, et cetera, they really are fairly well circumscribed.
take all these groups and throw them into one big pot and say, here, now you're a region of four COG areas, it doesn't work.
I chaired the steering committee that wrote the application for designation for that Central Texas Health Service area for the new health main body that we had created, the Health Systems Agency.
The HSAs, the Health Systems Agencies, were quite powerful as opposed to their predecessors.
voluntary health planning agencies called 314 agencies.
They just depended upon voluntary participation at the COG level.
And they didn't have any authority over dollars.
But the HSAs were organized as private and for-profit corporations, most of them.
And they had policy-making authority, and they had control of the budget of many millions of dollars of health money.
Well, that attracted great attention.
So whereas in the past, the advisory boards of the 314 agencies had been made up of consumers and others sort of voluntarily going along with things.
When these new agencies developed, there was a great deal of competition to make sure that you were on the board, you were represented somehow, and your hospital needed to be represented.
at saying your agency needed to be represented and your professional association needed to be represented.
So it was quite an experiment.
They developed health plans for the regions that were very complicated and very difficult to do.
Some of our health plan graduates participated in that all over the state of Texas.
Some of them actually ran the agencies.
And they did things that make sense in terms of regional planning.
For instance, you have a region and you have a comprehensive health plan, you would expect that all that various health components would fit into that.
Even if they were, even if there were state agencies, they ought to fit into that.
They're serving that area.
So, and in fact that's what occurred.
So it happened that all the state agencies that have health programs, and there are over, almost 30 of them that do, had to
be their plans and their activities had to be consistent with the health plan of the region.
Now that makes sense in terms of planning.
It's dynamite politically.
So when the Texas Commission on Alcoholism was developing their regional plans, they had to bring them before the HSAs, the health service areas, to be blessed.
And if they didn't get blessed, they had to go back and fix them until they were.
Now that makes sense in terms of planning.
It's rational.
It's totally rational.
On the other hand, these agencies weren't used to having anybody else look over their shoulders.
And they hated it.
So the agencies were alienated, the bureaucracy.
The politicians were alienated because these agencies, as nonprofit corporations, were not beholden to them.
The governor couldn't control them.
The mayors couldn't control them.
They looked more to Washington than they did to Austin for their sustenance.
And so they were...
Shades of the model cities program.
Yeah, it was almost, you could say, doomed from the start.
The providers didn't like me either because of these complicated consumers who kept asking silly questions.
Were they really silly?
No, they weren't silly at all.
They were questions that they had difficulty answering.
Probably too common sense oriented.
Not technically, I don't know.
I don't mean to defame the providers necessarily.
There were a lot of enthusiastic participants.
But when White came into office, although he had run on one of his planks was that he was going to save health planning.
In fact, he allowed the continued degeneration of the health planning system that had been started by his predecessor,
wild bill.
And it was under White's regime that all the federal funding was jerked by the state.
And they were, in fact, they were all wiped out.
It was all over.
And I think it was a very sad thing.
Now we see in Texas a resurgence of voluntary regional health funding back to the COG level again.
You don't have to participate, but it would be good if you did, et cetera.
And I chair that committee here in the region.
So the pendulum is swinging back.
Well, Don, at one time, as I remember locally here, when Humana was thinking of building a new hospital, St. Joseph's effectively blocked it for quite a long time.
They did it through the health planning system.
OK.
And what mechanism did the health planning system have?
Well, the idea was that in order to control costs that were rapidly increasing in the health sector, you had to control capital investment.
And if you could control capital investment, then you could control this expansion.
So the idea was that if you wanted to expand your facility,
Or if you wanted to add a new facility or add a new service, you had to get what was called a certificate of need from the state.
Not a certificate of demand, but a certificate of need.
You had to show that the community that you served, in fact, needed what you wanted to do.
Well, through that mechanism... That came from which organization?
Well, in Texas it was split.
You would think that would be under the group that's involved with implementation plans.

But in fact, there was a new health agency created by the legislature called the Texas Health Facilities Commission, which was not at all, was not in any way associated with the health department or with the health planning, state health planning.
So it was crazy.
And by definition, the commissioners of the Health Facilities Commission could not have had any prior experience with health facilities.
I was really nuts.
Anyway, so you had to go before this group and it was like a hearing.
In fact, it was exactly what it was.
They had a hearing and all the testimony had to be entered verbally.
There was nothing written that was accepted.
And you had to get up and present your case.
Humana argued that this area would continue to grow and that we needed additional beds.
general acute care and we also needed general additional beds for pediatric and OB and St. Joseph's argued the counter because it was not to their best interest for there to be increased competition.
That went on for about four years and the first time it came to the ruling
The commission ruled in favor of St. Joseph's totally and turned down Humanity completely.
So St. Joseph's was allowed to expand its OB and add new beds, and Humanity was not allowed to do anything.
Well, Humanity was furious, and they kept on fighting.
And then right about the time that they finally won, the Texas Health Facilities Commission, six weeks later, went out of business.
So it was a moot point anyway.
So now they've built and have opened up.
And the competition that we're seeing in the community, I think, is very healthy.
And, of course, we now have Scott and White.
Scott and White's here.
They're doing very well in Greenleaf's building, Sandstone's building.
What's happening is that we're seeing... We have a new building for the rehab center.
Yeah.
So we're seeing the development of the regional headquarters, the regional system, regional focus right here in Bryant College Station for health care.
And it's going to be...
It's just a pity, in my opinion, that
It all didn't happen as a center, as a medical complex somewhere within the Metropolitan area, rather than having one of the newer facilities, well, two of them.
Well, it would have if St. Joseph's hadn't fought Humana.
Humana's first proposal was to expand their current facility.
And when that was turned down, they said, we're leaving Bryan.
We're going to go to College Station.
We're going to build a whole new facility.
And up to that point, they intend to stay and enrich the health center that was developed.
There are various ways to look at it.
Really, the issue is access.
And in terms of access, we don't have very much of a problem here anyway.
And you can see that St. Joe's from this building will be there in less than 10 minutes.
In most urban areas, you have a hard time doing that.
Well, you can be almost anywhere within the area here in 10 minutes.
That's true.
But if you look at the future, which is really what we're planning for, it could very well be that their move south might end up being very smart.
In the area of psychiatric care, I think we're going to see this area become a regional center or a state center.
The reason for that is that there is a great deal of interest
people have traditionally in being hospitalized outside of their home communities for psychiatric illness.
There's a lot of stigma still associated with it.
If possible, they'll go outside the town.
Well, we're right in the middle of this huge urban triangle that will be one of the largest in the US.
It's massive.
It's going to be bigger.
So you can be hospitalized in College Station,
and your folks or your spouse or your family can visit you from San Antonio or Dallas or Austin or Waco or Houston without too much trouble you're within reach.
Some people have referred to our area as being centrally isolated.
Yeah, that may be it.
But it's been an interesting endeavor or exercise to see
this mix through the marketplaces really was having an impact.
And in health care delivery, planning is not so important regionally right now as it is institutionally.
The most important thing that, in Texas at least, that the regional health planning bodies do is provide a forum.
where health providers and others can come together and talk about things.
The networking, particularly, the bridging, potentially, is very important.
But the issue of control, that is developing, in fact, a regional plan and implementing it, is not one that we're likely to see come up again for a while.
It runs counter with the Texas values, that sort of centralization
The detections are just suspecting that.
Maybe a good reason, I'm not sure.
But that's just not the way we do things here, I guess, if they tell you.
There's another facility that we probably should mention.
That's the university's program for fitness with their sport medicine program.
And that ties in with the rehab center's work, I'm sure, and with all the cardiology
specialists in the area?
Yeah, this area is just really expanding.
In the last five years, the number of physicians has more than doubled.
We have virtually almost every specialty that you can imagine.
Better to have the physicians double than the lawyers double.
Well, they'll be behind me.
They'll be following me.
The more ambulances chasing me.
Oh, boy.
Don, we have now a new faculty member in health planning.
Would you go into that?
Sherry Bain is a nurse.
Part of her background is nursing.
She's a sociologist with a PhD in sociology from Michigan.
She joined our planning faculty in 86, 87.
She has very good research skills.
and has spent a lot of time working with the various health organizations in the administration.
She and I look forward to having more time to work together.
In the current position, we don't have much time to do that, to develop the health systems program.
She's currently half time in the department?
She's currently 25% with medicine, where she continues to serve as, I think, director.
or a coordinator of some such in the Center for Health Systems and Technology.
I think that that 75% split will stay through academic year 87, 88.
75% with us?
With us.
After that, she will probably be 100% with the plan.
That's the current plan at this point.
Okay, we've recently gone through a APA accreditation visit and they have written their comments and so forth and the department and the college have responded to their comments.
Do you have any views on that or anything you care to add?
We dealt with all the issues that they brought up.
And all of them had even been able to hire a new planner and person for the faculty.
And with the appointment of a permanent dean, that was the remaining problem, that they didn't have a permanent department here.
And with the appointment of Dr. McCarthy as permanent dean, then I'll be returning to the department in January of 88.
And that was the only thing that was holding us up for full accreditation, which
I feel sure that we'll get the next meeting at the front of the accreditation board, which I think is in October.
I believe it is.
I've recently interviewed at UT Arlington, and several of the faculty members expressed doubt that they would be re-accredited by EPA for various reasons.
And apparently it's becoming very difficult to get that accreditation now.
So if we get it, why not?
Well, we have no reason to believe that we won't.
The PAB has been very complimentary for the way the university has responded.
They said we needed more space, so the university built us space.
That's how we got that room up here.
They said we needed more faculty.
We got another faculty member.
And we'll be getting a permanent department head back, which will re-focus on the MUP degree, I would think, which was one of their complaints.
Yes.
Yeah, I think that's important, too.
Right now, I think for the fall, we're looking at 28 MUP and 28 MSLD and 40 doctoral students, in my opinion.
In my opinion, 20 doctoral students would be adequate, particularly if they were active.
Many of those 40 or ABDs will never finish.
You probably shouldn't be carrying them still.
But 40 doctoral students for high-sized factories is much too hard.
I don't know how we can do it responsibly.
And I really think the NDP should, to me, the NDP should be up.
It has a decent critical mass when it's up around 60 or 80.
I think 60 should be a minimum.
In SLD, I think it would be fairly self-regulated.
It probably won't get too much larger than it is.
But I think that there's some really interesting vitality that we can get from that mixture.
I think so.
The two groups are quite different in terms of the types of personalities they attract.
Oh, sure.
But I think that's useful.
So many times I see planners with a predictably adversarial perspective towards developers that may be well-deserved.
I mean, we all have seen unscrupulous developers.
They've screwed up a lot.
Yeah.
We've seen unscrupulous developers.
But actually, the cities really need entrepreneurs who provide capital and take risks.
And the entrepreneurs have a need for a city that's well-planned to protect their investments and to let them know how things are going to be in the future, et cetera.
So I really think that there's a potential for a symbiotic relationship instead of an adversarial one.
And I hope that these two groups of students in close proximity will precipitate some meaningful discussions.
And hopefully the MDPs who tend to be public sector-oriented
We'll learn to appreciate the needs of the entrepreneur.
And the MSLDs, who are entrepreneurial, will learn to appreciate something about the planners.
I heard one developer say that a planner's job was to see that you can't do yours.
So it goes both ways, you see.
And that's unfortunate.
That doesn't have to be that way either.
I think there are good examples where developers have approached cities very responsibly.
And there were planning staffs who worked with developers to achieve a project of value that would never have been possible otherwise.
And I think it's important that our students be socialized in professional school to have what I think would be a healthier attitude.
We ought not to be unnecessarily adversarial.
I think if you've got a guy that's out to rape the public, then it is our responsibility.
I think it's OK to be watchful, but not adversarial.
If it weren't for people willing to pick up the responsibility for entrepreneurial enterprise, then we'd end up with state-run capitalism.
And that would lead to a pretty dead type of hand on development.
I think the department offers a very interesting mix of attitudes.
They take a course with you, and they get the planning gospel according to Cornish.
And they take one with Chewy, and they get it according to Hinojosa.
And then Rosa's got his own version, and Pew's got his version.
And they take it from me, and it's another perspective.
And I think that's important because there is no one perspective.
I remember Nietzsche said...
This is my way.
What's your way?
The way doesn't exist.
And that's important.
They have to develop their own professional ethics and their own professional perspectives on things.
Well, it troubles the students because they don't know this.
And we have to tell them if they really come to a point where it's becoming a mental problem for them that they can't seem to adjust to all of the various philosophies while they're in school.
And I always tell them not to expect to do it until they're out of school for two or three years.
Then we'll all start coming together.
When it does, they'll know it.
They really do.
I think the doctoral program is very important because we need to have a good theoretical framework for the field.
You know, we're such an eclectic profession that really our theoretical base comes from other disciplines.
We are essentially applied sociology.
I think it's important that we spend some time working on theory.
A lot of our great, many of our doctoral research endeavors in the past have been extremely applied.
I think there's room for theory.
Theory is ultimately very practical because it explains things.
It gives a framework, a construct for which to view things.
I'm delighted to hear you say that for several reasons.
One, I teach the course.
And two, I think that theory is very practical because it gives the student a shorthand way of analyzing problems.
And he can or she can deal with them very effectively and very quickly.
understanding what the theoretical framework is that they're dealing with.

We have a lot to learn, I think, or we've perhaps already learned it, but we need to incorporate it knowing that we're getting it from sociology and psychology, particularly small group psychology, political science, economics, even some in management.
Management is another eclectic endeavor as well.
I think particularly the behavioral sciences
Architecture, I don't think, has much of a theoretical framework either.
We do, of course, deal with design issues.
I think whatever architecture has to offer us, we ought to become cognizant of.
That's one of the things I think that bothers me.
It seems that we're moving away from the design base that our disciplines have in the past.
Maybe that's not bad, I suppose, but it
I would like to see our students exposed, at least, a little more systematically.
That is to say that we don't allow a student to miss exposure to design.
They pick it up, but without a better design base than some of them have.
I don't think they pick up very much of it.
We used to be very visual and very design-oriented.
Now we're much more analytical and textually-oriented.

That may be simply commentary of the sign of the times, but it seems to me that there's something to be said for a person not really understanding the urban design issues when we're talking about urban planning.
Planning, I'm always bothered by that a little bit.
Planning is simply a function of management.
We are those people who have decided to specialize in one aspect of planning.
urban or regional setting.
One aspect of management.
Well, no, really one aspect of planning.
One manifestation of planning.
Because we tend to deal primarily with the physical.
Planning of physical.
Physical planning.
I think I'm probably less so.
I'm involved more with health systems than with health facilities.
There are always facilities, manifestations of that.
But I'm...
I think that this department probably has a reputation of being strong in physical planning.
And that probably is the result of the backgrounds of the faculty.
But that has been changing over the years.
And it will continue to change as some of us retire who have had strong physical design backgrounds.
Well, I think it's important that we replace people who are leaving with
with faculty who have similar orientations in that respect.

The department will probably be having to look for people with PhDs more and more, since we're going much more into research orientation at the University in general, and our college in particular, than we ever have before.
The chances of getting somebody with a design background are remote, then.
It's not easy.
They're around.
People who have a design background, a planning background, both academic and professional, who also have PhDs.
What has surprised me about the program here is that it hasn't been more physically design-oriented than it has, considering the faculty.
And I think the faculty has, in fact, made an effort

to accommodate the changing forces on planning profession as they've come into view with the, for example, the urban riots and the need for understanding the social aspects of planning and how they generate the needs for physical accommodation and also political
And of course, Jim Gartner was particularly strong there.
He was an elected official on several occasions.
And then the new era of economic concerns that we've all got to get up to speed on.
Yeah, I think that's true.
I think the new religion of economic development
It's very important that our students are exposed to the economic issues.
I mean, a city is an economic entity.
That's why it exists.
It deals with the basic economic issues of life, shelter, food, security.
Need for specialization.
What struck me as being interesting was a comment made by Terry Kahn in Austin this Tuesday.
And they have a land development emphasis within their MEP program, which is quite well defined.
And that faculty feels that it's more appropriate
for their MSNCP degree to have it a well-defined area of concern within the master's in planning degree rather than going for an MS in land development.
Here we have not chosen to do that.
We have our MS in land development and NEP, as I say, are separate degrees.
I would hope that there's some cross-fertilization.
I think there is.
I think it tends, the land development emphasis tends to have more of an impact on the planning students than the planning students do on the land development students, which I think is unfortunate.
So far, I think that's true.
How do you, what anticipations do you have for next year, moving back to the department?
